'''Moïse Bombito Lumpungu''' (born March 30, 2000) is a Canadian professional [[soccer]] player who plays as a [[centre-back]] for [[Ligue 1]] club [[OGC Nice|Nice]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

==Early life==
Born in [[Montreal]], Quebec, Bombito is of Congolese descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://afriquinfos.com/la-determination-des-africains-du-canada-na-pas-suffi-a-empecher-messi-datteindre-la-finale-de-la-copa-america-2024/|title=La détermination des 'Africains du Canada' face à Messi|first=Afriquinfos|last=Editeur|date=July 11, 2024}}</ref> He began his youth soccer career with [[CS St-Laurent]], where he initially played as a forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rds.ca/soccer/mls/un-quebecois-sur-la-voie-rapide-au-colorado-1.16677287|title=" Ça va juste trop vite " : la fulgurante progression de Moïse Bombito|trans-title="It's just going too fast": the dazzling progress of Moïse Bombito|language=fr|date=February 26, 2023|first=Nicolas|last=Landry|work=[[Réseau des sports|RDS]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://burgundywave.com/2023/06/14/moise-bombito-canada-nations-league/|title=Moïse Bombito Canada Callup: From Community College to the National Team in Two Years|date=June 14, 2023|first=Matt|last=Pollard|work=Burgundy Wave}}</ref> At the age of 18, he declined an opportunity to join [[CS St-Hubert]] in the semi-professional [[Première ligue de soccer du Québec]], choosing to remain with St-Laurent in the amateur [[Ligue de soccer élite du Québec]] to prioritize consistent playing time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lapresse.ca/sports/soccer/2023-02-17/moise-bombito/toujours-dejouer-les-pronostics.php|title=Moïse Bombito: Toujours déjouer les pronostics|trans-title=Moïse Bombito: Always beat the odds|first=Justin|last=Vézina|date=February 17, 2023|language=fr|work=[[La Presse (Canadian newspaper)|La Presse]]}}</ref>

==College career==
Bombito originally attended [[Collège Ahuntsic]] and played for their men's soccer team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegeahuntsic.qc.ca/notre-college/nouvelles/charles-auguste-moise-lumpungu-bombito-deux-anciens-des-aigles-ont-ete-repeches-dans-des-clubs-de-la-major-league-soccer-mls|title=Charles Auguste et Moïse Lumpungu Bombito, deux anciens des Aigles, repêchés par la Major League Soccer (MLS) !|trans-title=Charles Auguste and Moïse Lumpungu Bombito, two former Eagles, drafted by Major League Soccer (MLS)!|language=fr|date=February 22, 2023|work=[[Collège Ahuntsic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|trans-title=Moïse Bombito: the journey of the least known Quebecer in the MLS|language=fr|url=https://www.journaldemontreal.com/2023/06/14/moise-bombito-le-parcours-du-quebecois-le-moins-connu-de-la-mls|date=June 14, 2023|title=Moïse Bombito: le parcours du Québécois le moins connu de la MLS|first=Dave|last=Lévesque|work=[[Le Journal de Montréal]]}}</ref> In 2019, he was named to the [[RSEQ]] all-star team for Division 1 soccer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collegeahuntsic.qc.ca/notre-college/nouvelles/equipes-etoiles-du-rseq-2019-2020|date=November 19, 2019|title=2019-2020 RSEQ All-Star Teams|work=[[Collège Ahuntsic]]}}</ref>

After attending a combine hosted by [[António Ribeiro (soccer, born 1980)|António Ribeiro]] and [[Frederico Moojen]], he began attending junior college in the United States, joining [[Iowa Western Community College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lapremiereronde.com/moise-bombito-cogne-a-la-porte-de-la-mls/|title=Moïse Bombito cogne à la porte de la MLS|trans-title=Moïse Bombito knocks on the door of the MLS|language=fr|date=January 2023|work=La Premiere Ronde|first=Richard Jr|last=Luemba}}</ref> He played two seasons, finishing as national runner-up in the 2021 spring season, following it up with a national championship in the fall 2021 season.<ref name=unhprof /> He earned 2021 All-American accolades, was named the ICCAC Tournament MVP, and was selected to the ICCAC All-Tournament Team and the ICCAC All-Region First Team.<ref name=unhprof>{{cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/sports/mens-soccer/roster/moise-bombito/9633|title=Moise Bombito UNH profile|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref>

In 2022, he transferred to the [[University of New Hampshire]] to play for the [[New Hampshire Wildcats men's soccer|men's soccer team]] at the [[NCAA Division I]] level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/8/11/mens-soccer-9-mens-soccer-adds-10-student-athletes-to-2022-roster.aspx|title=#9 Men's Soccer Adds 10 Student-Athletes to 2022 Roster|date=August 11, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> On September 10, 2022, Bombito made his collegiate debut and also scored his first goal against the [[FIU Panthers men's soccer|FIU Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/9/10/mens-soccer-wildcats-defeat-florida-international-3-0.aspx|title=Wildcats Defeat Florida International, 3-0|date=September 10, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> That season, he was named the team MVP,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2023/5/11/mens-soccer-announces-team-awards.aspx|title=Men's Soccer Announces Team Awards|date=May 11, 2023|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] Defensive Player of the Year,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Moise Bombito & Marc Hubbard Win ECAC Major Awards|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/19/mens-soccer-moise-bombito-marc-hubbard-win-ecac-major-awards.aspx|date=December 19, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> the [[America East Conference|America East]] Defender of the Year,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/11/10/mens-soccer-22-unh-wins-three-america-east-major-awards.aspx|title=#22 UNH Wins Three America East Major Awards|date=November 10, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> was named to the All-ECAC First Team and All-America East First Team,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/21/mens-soccer-three-wildcats-selected-in-mls-superdraft-moise-bombito-picked-third-overall.aspx|title=Three Wildcats Selected in MLS SuperDraft; Moise Bombito Picked Third Overall|date=December 21, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> and a Second Team All-American.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/9/moise-bombito-yannick-bright-earn-all-america-honors.aspx|title=Moise Bombito & Yannick Bright Earn All-America Honors|date=December 9, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> He was also a MAC Hermann Trophy Semifinalist,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/7/mens-soccer-moise-bombito-named-mac-hermann-trophy-semifinalist.aspx|title=Moise Bombito Named MAC Hermann Trophy Semifinalist|date=December 7, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> was invited to play in the MLS College Showcase,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/8/mens-soccer-moise-bombito-yannick-bright-to-attend-mls-college-showcase.aspx|title=Moise Bombito & Yannick Bright to Attend MLS College Showcase|date=December 8, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> and became the first UNH player to be selected to the [[Generation Adidas]] class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2022/12/19/mens-soccer-moise-bombito-named-to-2023-mls-generation-adidas-class-watch-party-scheduled-for-wednesday.aspx|title=Bombito Named to 2023 MLS Generation adidas Class; Watch Party Scheduled for Wednesday|date=December 19, 2022|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref> During his sole season with the school, he scored four goals, including two game winners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unhwildcats.com/news/2023/6/14/mens-soccer-moise-bombito-selected-to-canadian-national-team-roster.aspx|title=Moise Bombito Selected to Canadian National Team Roster|date=June 14, 2023|work=[[New Hampshire Wildcats]]}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early===
In 2020, Bombito began playing with [[CS St-Hubert]] in the [[Première ligue de soccer du Québec]], where he converted to centre-back.<ref name=revel>{{Cite web|work=Viau Park|url=https://viaupark.ca/2020/10/22/moise-bombito-lumpungu-se-revele-en-plsq/|title=Moise Bombito Lumpungu se révèle en PLSQ|trans-title=Moise Bombito Lumpungu reveals himself in PLSQ|language=fr|first=Marc|last=Tougas|date=October 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journaldemontreal.com/2023/02/15/moise-bombito-le-quebecois-oublie|title=Moïse Bombito, le Québécois oublié|language=fr|date=February 15, 2023|trans-title=Moïse Bombito, the forgotten Quebecer|first=Marc-Antoine|last=Malo|work=[[Le Journal de Montréal]]}}</ref>

In 2022, Bombito played for the [[Seacoast United Phantoms]] in the [[USL League Two]], helping them win the Northeast Division title and being named to the USL League Two Team of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seacoastunited.demosphere-secure.com/about/news/seacoast-united-news-articles/moise-bombito-to-feature-in-mls-college-showcase|title=Moise Bombito to feature in MLS College Showcase|work=[[Seacoast United Phantoms]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/news/q-a-get-to-know-center-back-superdraft-pick-moise-bombito|title=Q&A: Get to know SuperDraft pick Moise Bombito|first=Sydney|last=Kohne|date=January 17, 2023|work=[[Colorado Rapids]]}}</ref>

===Colorado Rapids===
On December 21, 2022, Bombito signed a [[Generation Adidas]] contract and was selected in the first round (3rd overall) of the [[2023 MLS SuperDraft]] by the [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/mls/2022/12/19/montreals-moise-bombito-named-to-generation-adidas-class-ahead-of-mls-superdraft.html|title=Montreal's Moise Bombito named to Generation Adidas class ahead of MLS SuperDraft|date=December 19, 2022|work=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Neil|last=Davidson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/montreal/article/montreals-bombito-selected-third-by-colorado-rapids-in-mls-superdraft/|title=Montreal's Bombito selected third by Colorado Rapids in MLS SuperDraft|date=December 22, 2022|work=[[CTV News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://onesoccer.ca/a/it-hasn-t-sunk-in-yet-moise-bombito-s-looks-back-on-wild-18-month-journey-from-junior-college-to-mls|title="It hasn't sunk in yet": Moïse Bombito's looks back on wild 18 month journey from Junior College to MLS|date=March 3, 2023|work=[[OneSoccer]]|first=Alexandre|last=Gangué-Ruzic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/news/colorado-rapids-select-moise-bombito-and-oliver-semmle-in-the-2023-mls-superdraf|title=Colorado Rapids select Moise Bombito and Oliver Semmle in the 2023 MLS SuperDraft presented by adidas|date=December 21, 2022|work=[[Colorado Rapids]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/mls-super-draft-moise-bombito-canada-soccer-colorado-rapids-1.6694520|title=Canada's Bombito, Afrifa selected in top 10 of MLS SuperDraft|date=December 21, 2022|work=[[CBC Sports]]}}</ref> He became the first player from the University of New Hampshire to be selected in the first round of the draft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eu.seacoastonline.com/story/sports/2022/12/22/unh-moise-bombito-mls-superdraft-colorado-rapids/69747996007/|title=Moise Bombito 'so grateful' to be picked third in MLS SuperDraft, making UNH soccer history|first=Brandon|last=Brown|work=Portsmouth Herald}}</ref> After being an unused substitute in the opening match of the season, he suffered a knee injury during training, causing him to miss the next few weeks of action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2023/03/07/colorado-rapids-moise-bombito-injury|website=[[Denver Post]]|title=Colorado Rapids rookie center back Moïse Bombito out "a few weeks at least" with MCL injury|first=Brendan|last=Ploen|date=March 7, 2023}}</ref>

On May 7, Bombito made his debut for the Rapids' second team, [[Colorado Rapids 2]], in [[MLS Next Pro]] against [[LA Galaxy II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/news/it-s-a-privilege-moise-bombito-adds-youth-depth-and-intelligence-to-rapids-back-|title="It's a privilege": Moïse Bombito adds youth, depth and intelligence to Rapids' back line after injury|date=May 18, 2023|work=[[Colorado Rapids]]|first=Sydney|last=Kohne}}</ref> He made his [[Major League Soccer]] debut on May 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rds.ca/soccer/ligue-des-nations-moise-bombito-s-amene-en-renfort-pour-le-canada-1.17235018|title=Moïse Bombito s'amène en renfort pour le Canada|trans-title=Moïse Bombito comes as reinforcements for Canada|language=fr|date=June 10, 2023|work=[[Réseau des sports|RDS]]}}</ref> On May 24, he earned his first start for the Rapids in a [[U.S. Open Cup]] match against [[Real Salt Lake]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/news/he-s-got-a-bright-future-moise-bombito-builds-trust-within-team-through-first-st|title="He's got a bright future": Moïse Bombito builds trust within team through first start|date=May 25, 2023|first=Taylor|last=Gregorio|work=[[Colorado Rapids]]}}</ref> On March 30, 2024, he scored his first MLS goal in a 3–2 victory over [[Los Angeles FC]], which coincided with his 24th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2024/03/30/colorado-rapids-late-burst-lafc-victory/|title=Colorado Rapids ride late burst to beat MLS runner-up LAFC at home|first=Braidon|last=Nourse|date=March 30, 2024|work=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref>

===Nice===
On August 19, 2024, Bombito transferred to French [[Ligue 1]] side [[OGC Nice|Nice]], signing a contract until June 2028 for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ogcnice.com/en/article/127394/welcome-moise-bombito.html | title=Welcome Moïse Bombito! }}</ref> In their release, the Rapids stated the sale "breaks the MLS record fee for a center back while also surpassing Colorado’s outbound transfer record."{{citation needed|date=October 2025}} Bombito made his Nice debut on August 25 against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|date=August 25, 2024|title=Moïse Bombito becomes Canada’s third Ligue 1 debutant of the summer with OGC Nice bow|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2024/08/25/moise-bombito-becomes-canadas-third-ligue-1-debutant-of-the-summer-with-ogc-nice-bow/}}</ref>

After missing the [[Southern Derby]] due to a red card suspension, Bombito played every minute of Nice's remaining games in September, October and November. On September 25, 2024, the Canadian defender made his [[UEFA Europa League]] debut, starting in a group phase game versus [[Real Sociedad]].

On 5 October 2025, Bombito suffered a left tibia fracture during a 2–2 draw with [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], following an entanglement with [[Folarin Balogun]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kloke |first=Joshua |date=2025-10-05 |title=Moise Bombito injury: What comes next for Canada? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6692162/2025/10/05/moise-bombito-injury-what-comes-next-for-canada/ |access-date=2025-10-05 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bombito had only recently returned to action after a four-month injury spell, which was caused by both a wrist fracture and a tibia stress fracture.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Staff |first=Sportsnet |date=2025-10-05 |title=Canadian defender Moise Bombito stretchered off with leg injury |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/ligue-1/article/canadian-defender-moise-bombito-stretchered-off-with-leg-injury/ |access-date=2025-10-05 |website=Sportsnet.ca |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
In June 2023, Bombito was named to the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canadian national team]] for the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]], as an injury replacement for [[Derek Cornelius]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canada-soccer-men-moise-bombito-roster-1.6872468|title=Canada adds MLS defender Moise Bombito to CONCACAF Nations League roster|date=June 10, 2023|work=[[CBC Sports]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coloradorapids.com/news/colorado-rapids-defender-moise-bombito-called-up-to-canada-men-s-national-team-a|title=Colorado Rapids defender Moïse Bombito called up to Canada Men's National Team ahead of Concacaf Nations League Finals|date=June 10, 2023|work=[[Colorado Rapids]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadiansoccerdaily.com/2023/06/12/john-herdman-compares-first-time-canmnt-call-up-moise-bombitos-potential-to-jonathan-david/|title=Canada head coach John Herdman compares first-time CanMNT call-up Moïse Bombito's potential to Jonathan David|first=Tom|last=Nightingale|work=Canadian Soccer Daily|date=June 12, 2023}}</ref> He became the second-fastest Generation Adidas player to earn a national team call-up (171 days after the draft), behind only national team teammate [[Cyle Larin]].<ref>{{cite web|title=How Colorado Rapids' Moïse Bombito used "gauntlet mentality" to go from community college to Canadian men's national team|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2023/06/18/rapids-moise-bombito-gauntlet-mentality-canada/|date=June 18, 2023|work=[[The Denver Post]]|first=Brendan|last=Ploen}}</ref> He was then subsequently named to the 23-man squad for the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/canmnt-announces-final-23-man-squad-for-concacaf-gold-cup|date=June 19, 2023|work=[[Canadian Premier League]]|title=CanMNT announces final 23-man squad for Concacaf Gold Cup|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke}}</ref> Bombito made his debut in the opening match of the tournament on June 27 against [[Guadeloupe national football team|Guadeloupe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/mls-rookies-amhed-bombito-inspire-in-canada-s-gold-cup-opener|title=MLS rookies Amhed, Bombito inspire in Canada's Gold Cup opener|work=[[Major League Soccer]]|first=Ben|last=Steiner|date=June 28, 2023}}</ref>

In June 2024, Bombito was named to Canada's squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|work= [[Canadian Soccer Association]]}}</ref> He played every minute of the tournament, providing an assist in the semifinal match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], which Canada ultimately lost on penalties.

